ABORT(3)                                                                                                    Linux Programmer's Manual                                                                                                    ABORT(3)

NNAAMMEE
       abort - cause abnormal process termination

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ##iinncclluuddee <<ssttddlliibb..hh>>

       vvooiidd aabboorrtt((vvooiidd));;

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       The  aabboorrtt()  first unblocks the SSIIGGAABBRRTT signal, and then raises that signal for the calling process (as though rraaiissee(3) was called).  This results in the abnormal termination of the process unless the SSIIGGAABBRRTT signal is caught and the
       signal handler does not return (see lloonnggjjmmpp(3)).

       If the aabboorrtt() function causes process termination, all open streams are closed and flushed.

       If the SSIIGGAABBRRTT signal is ignored, or caught by a handler that returns, the aabboorrtt() function will still terminate the process.  It does this by restoring the default disposition for SSIIGGAABBRRTT and then raising  the  signal  for  a  second
       time.

RREETTUURRNN VVAALLUUEE
       The aabboorrtt() function never returns.

AATTTTRRIIBBUUTTEESS
       For an explanation of the terms used in this section, see aattttrriibbuutteess(7).

       ┌──────────┬───────────────┬─────────┐
       │IInntteerrffaaccee │ AAttttrriibbuuttee     │ VVaalluuee   │
       ├──────────┼───────────────┼─────────┤
       │aabboorrtt()   │ Thread safety │ MT-Safe │
       └──────────┴───────────────┴─────────┘
CCOONNFFOORRMMIINNGG TTOO
       SVr4, POSIX.1-2001, POSIX.1-2008, 4.3BSD, C89, C99.

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       ggddbb(1), ssiiggaaccttiioonn(2), eexxiitt(3), lloonnggjjmmpp(3), rraaiissee(3)

